\/dev1234\/dios\/0\/drive.Description: When on (1), the corresponding 8-bit bus is in output mode. When off (0), it is in input mode. Bit 0 corresponds to the least significant byte. For example, the value 1 drives the least significant byte, the value 8 drives the most significant byte.

\/dev1234\/dios\/0\/output.Description: Sets the value of the DIO output for those bytes where 'drive' is enabled.

Options.0: "manual": Enables manual control of the DIO output bits.
Options.1: "awg_sequencer_commands": Enables setting the DIO output values by AWG sequencer commands and forwards DIO input values to the AWG sequencer. The DIO interface operates at a clock frequency of 150 MHz.
Options.2: "dio_codeword": Enables setting the DIO output values by AWG sequencer commands and forwards DIO input values to the AWG sequencer. This mode is equivalent to the mode AWG Sequencer, except for the DIO interface clock frequency which is set to 50 MHz.
Options.3: "qccs": Enables setting the DIO output values by the ZSync input values. Forwards the ZSync input values to the AWG sequencer. Forwards the DIO input values to the ZSync output. Select this mode when the instrument is connected via ZSync to a PQSC.

\/dev1234\/dios\/0\/input.Description: Gives the value of the DIO input for those bytes where drive is disabled.

\/dev1234\/dios\/0\/interface.Description: Selects the interface standard to use on the 32-bit DIO interface. A value of 0 means that a 3.3 V CMOS interface is used. A value of 1 means that an LVDS compatible interface is used.

\/dev1234\/system\/awg\/channelgrouping.Description: Sets the channel grouping mode of the device.

Options.0: "groups_of_2": Use the outputs in groups of 2. One sequencer program controls 2 outputs (use /dev..../awgs/0..4/).
Options.1: "groups_of_4": Use the outputs in groups of 4. One sequencer program controls 4 outputs (use /dev..../awgs/0/ and /dev..../awgs/2/)
Options.2: "groups_of_8": Use the outputs in groups of 8. One sequencer program controls 8 outputs (use /dev..../awgs/0/). Requires 8 channel device.

Options.0: "internal": The internal clock is used as the frequency and time base reference.
Options.1: "external": An external clock is intended to be used as the frequency and time base reference. Provide a clean and stable 10MHz or 100MHz reference to the appropriate back panel connector.
Options.2: "zsync": A ZSync clock is intended to be used as the frequency and time base reference.

Options.0: "locked": Reference clock has been locked on.
Options.1: "error": There was an error locking onto the reference clock signal. After an error the source is automatically switched back to internal reference clock.
Options.2: "busy": The device is busy trying to lock onto the reference clock signal.

\/dev1234\/system\/clocks\/referencecloc.Description: Indicates the frequency of the reference clock.

\/dev1234\/system\/clocks\/sampleclock\/.Description: Indicates the frequency of the sample clock. Changing the sample clock temporarily interrupts the AWG sequencers.

Options.0: Sample clock signal is valid and has been locked on.
Options.1: There was an error adjusting the sample clock.
Options.2: The device is busy trying to adjust the sample clock.

Options.0: "api": Oscillators are controlled by the UI/API.
Options.1: "awg_sequencer": Oscillators are controlled by the AWG sequencer.

Options.1: "free_running": Free Running: The counter runs on a repetitive time base defined by the Period field. At the beginning of each period the counter is reset, and at the end, the accumulated number of counts is output.
Options.2: "gated_free_running": Gated Free Running: The counter runs on a repetitive time base defined by the Period field. The Gate Input signal controls when the unit counter is allowed to run. The counter as well as the timer is reset when the Gate Input signal is low. The counter will only deliver new values if the Gate Input signal is high for a time longer than the configured Period.
Options.3: "gated": Gated: The counter is controlled with the Gate Input signal. The counter is enabled at the rising edge of the Gate Input signal and disabled at the falling edge. Pulses are counted as long as the counter is enabled. The accumulated number of counts is output on the falling edge of the Gate Input signal.
Options.4: "time_tagging": Time Tagging: Every pulse is detected individually and tagged with the time of the event. The Period defines the minimum hold-off time between the tagging of two subsequent pulses. If more than one pulse occurs within the window defined by the Period, then the pulses are accumulated and output at the end of the window. The Period effectively determines the maximum rate at which pulse information can be transmitted to the host PC.

Options.1: "free_running": Free Running: The counter runs on a repetitive time base defined by the Period field. At the beginning of each period the counter is reset, and at the end, the accumulated number of counts is output.
Options.2: "gated_free_running": Gated Free Running: The counter runs on a repetitive time base defined by the Period field. The Gate Input signal controls when the unit counter is allowed to run. The counter as well as the timer is reset when the Gate Input signal is low. The counter will only deliver new values if the Gate Input signal is high for a time longer than the configured Period.
Options.3: "gated": Gated: The counter is controlled with the Gate Input signal. The counter is enabled at the rising edge of the Gate Input signal and disabled at the falling edge. Pulses are counted as long as the counter is enabled. The accumulated number of counts is output on the falling edge of the Gate Input signal.
Options.4: "time_tagging": Time Tagging: Every pulse is detected individually and tagged with the time of the event. The Period defines the minimum hold-off time between the tagging of two subsequent pulses. If more than one pulse occurs within the window defined by the Period, then the pulses are accumulated and output at the end of the window. The Period effectively determines the maximum rate at which pulse information can be transmitted to the host PC.

Options.3: DIO Bit 3.
Options.4: DIO Bit 4.

\/dev1234\/cnts\/6\/integrate.Description: Sum up counter values over time.

\/dev1234\/cnts\/6\/trigrising.Description: Performs a trigger event when the source signal crosses the trigger level from low to high. For dual edge triggering, select also the falling edge.

\/dev1234\/cnts\/6\/trigfalling.Description: Performs a trigger event when the source signal crosses the trigger level from high to low. For dual edge triggering, select also the rising edge.
